        Multi-Storey vs Single-Storey Brisbane Homes: Buyer Pool Dynamics That Shape the Sale
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Whether a Brisbane home is one level or two changes who buys it, how they value it, and how the campaign should be calibrated. Here is how seller strategy should adapt.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The decision to buy a single-storey home or a multi-storey home is rarely framed by buyers as a feature comparison. It is almost always framed as a life-stage decision: a young family that wants the children's bedrooms upstairs and the living downstairs, a downsizer that does not want to climb stairs every day, an investor that wants the floorplan that rents fastest in a given suburb, an extended-family arrangement that needs a separation between generations. The seller's task is not to argue that one type is better than the other; it is to understand who is most likely to buy this particular property and to calibrate the campaign so that the right buyer pool sees it on the right terms.</p>

      <p>This article walks through the demographic patterns of single-storey versus multi-storey buyer pools in Brisbane's inner east, the per-square-metre price differences, the floorplan elements that matter to each pool, the condition and accessibility considerations, and a practical framework for sellers calibrating campaign positioning.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The single-storey buyer pool</h2>
      <p>Single-storey homes in Brisbane attract three distinct buyer types: downsizers leaving a multi-storey family home and prioritising no-stairs living, young families who prefer the supervisory ease of a single-level layout for very young children, and accessibility-driven buyers (older buyers, buyers with mobility considerations, or buyers planning for ageing in place). The combined pool is large, but it is concentrated in particular price brackets and suburbs. In Brisbane's inner east, a quality single-storey on a level block in a desirable street faces unusually intense competition because all three of these pools are active simultaneously, and a well-presented home can attract very strong campaigns.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The multi-storey buyer pool</h2>
      <p>Multi-storey homes in the inner east overwhelmingly attract families with school-age children, where the convention of bedrooms upstairs and living downstairs creates the day-to-day separation that families value. The pool also includes professionals seeking a study or work-from-home zone above living areas, multi-generational households where one level can serve as semi-independent accommodation, and buyers prioritising views or air flow that comes with elevation. The pool is somewhat narrower than the single-storey pool because the no-stairs preference among downsizers and accessibility buyers is genuine, but it is deep and price-resilient at the family-buyer end.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why a single-storey can command a per-square-metre premium</h2>
      <p>On a per-square-metre basis, single-storey homes in many inner east suburbs trade at a noticeable premium over equivalent multi-storey homes. The reason is land. A single-storey footprint uses more land for the same internal floor area, and land is the scarce resource in inner Brisbane. A 200-square-metre single-storey home on 600 square metres of land typically incorporates more usable garden, more outdoor connection from living areas, and a building footprint that hugs the block in ways multi-storey homes do not. Combined with the breadth of the buyer pool (downsizers plus families plus accessibility), the single-storey premium is real and persistent in the inner east.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why a multi-storey can deliver more home for the dollar</h2>
      <p>For a given total price, a multi-storey home typically delivers more internal floor area than a single-storey on the same block. Family buyers in particular often prefer the additional bedrooms and bathrooms over the additional outdoor space that a single-storey would offer. A four-bedroom multi-storey on 405 square metres of land may suit a young family far better than a three-bedroom single-storey on 600 square metres at the same price point, even though the per-square-metre figure looks less attractive. The seller's marketing should emphasise the floor area, the number of bedrooms, the separation between sleeping and living, and the practical functionality of the layout rather than focusing on the per-square-metre comparison.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The downsizer factor and its weight in pricing</h2>
      <p>Downsizers in Brisbane's inner east form a meaningful slice of the single-storey buyer pool, and their search behaviour has distinctive characteristics. They typically have substantial equity from the sale of a larger home, are not constrained by finance pre-approval ceilings to the same extent, and are highly motivated when the right single-storey property comes up. They also screen aggressively: more than one or two steps to a front door, a sloping driveway that complicates car access, a long internal corridor, a distant laundry, or a small main bedroom can all eliminate a property from a downsizer's shortlist regardless of price. Sellers of single-storey homes who address these screening criteria explicitly attract a stronger campaign than those who do not.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The family-buyer factor for multi-storey homes</h2>
      <p>Family buyers evaluating multi-storey homes screen on a different set of criteria. The arrangement of bedrooms upstairs, the location of the main bedroom relative to the children's rooms, the presence or absence of a second living area, the connection between kitchen and outdoor entertaining, the position of the laundry, and the storage available throughout all matter. They also care about the staircase: open-tread staircases worry parents of toddlers; staircases without handrails on both sides worry parents of older children; long unbroken stair runs read as more dangerous than runs with intermediate landings. Sellers of multi-storey homes who present a layout that solves family-life problems consistently produce stronger campaigns.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Floorplan elements buyers focus on</h2>
      <p>For single-storey homes, buyers focus on the connection between living and outdoor space, the natural light through the floorplan, the location of the main bedroom relative to the front of the home (back-of-home main bedrooms are usually preferred), the size and accessibility of the laundry, and the availability of a second living area for family separation. For multi-storey homes, the focus shifts to the separation of zones, the practicality of the staircase, the size of the upstairs landing, the placement of bathrooms relative to bedrooms, and the presence of a downstairs bedroom or study that can serve flexible roles. These priorities should shape both the pre-listing presentation work and the marketing copy itself.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Condition cues that matter at each level</h2>
      <p>Multi-storey homes carry condition cues that single-storey homes do not. Staircase wear, balustrade integrity, second-floor flooring deflection, upstairs balcony or deck condition, and the watertightness of upstairs wet areas above downstairs ceilings all attract inspector and buyer attention. Pre-listing repairs that address these items quietly (loose treads, scuffed balustrades, cracked grout in upstairs bathrooms) prevent buyer concerns from compounding into broader doubts about the home. For single-storey homes, the equivalent attention should go to the front entry path, internal door thresholds, level access from indoors to outdoors, and the condition of timber floors that often show their age more visibly than stair treads do.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Accessibility as a marketing factor</h2>
      <p>For single-storey homes, accessibility is rarely called out explicitly in marketing because doing so can shift the buyer perception toward older-buyer territory, which can be polarising. The better approach is to present the property as easy-living rather than as accessible, and to let the buyer's own evaluation arrive at the accessibility conclusion. Photographs of clean entry sequences, level outdoor access, wide doorways, and uncluttered corridors do more useful work than copy claims about accessibility. For multi-storey homes, accessibility is rarely a marketing story, but the placement of any downstairs bedroom or study deserves emphasis where it could function as a guest room, granny flat, or secondary main bedroom in the future.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Renovating between levels: when it makes sense</h2>
      <p>Single-storey homes are sometimes raised and built under to add a second storey, and multi-storey homes are sometimes refigured to repurpose an underused upstairs into a more functional zone. These projects are major capital decisions and rarely make sense as a pre-listing renovation; the cost-to-benefit equation works only for owners who plan to live in the modified home for years. Sellers contemplating a between-level renovation specifically to lift sale price should run the numbers carefully with a quantity surveyor and an experienced agent before committing. The far more common right answer is to present the home as it currently is, well-maintained and well-staged, and let the buyer pool calibrate the price accordingly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical framework for sellers</h2>
      <p>Begin by identifying the most likely buyer pool for your specific property. A three-bedroom single-storey on a level block: probably downsizers and small families. A four-bedroom multi-storey with two living areas: probably school-age families. A two-storey home with a downstairs bedroom suite: possibly extended-family buyers. Calibrate the campaign accordingly: photography that emphasises the features that pool cares about, copy that solves the problems that pool is trying to solve, agent briefings that reflect how that pool is likely to evaluate the property. The right campaign for a multi-storey family home is materially different from the right campaign for a downsizer-friendly single-storey, and the seller who recognises the distinction outperforms the seller who treats them as interchangeable.</p>

